The *Orders* App Template is a collection of UI- and application patterns, components and best practices, packaged into a consistent production quality application ready to be used as a starting point or for reference. The patterns used in each App Template can be used independently and combined into new applications.

*Orders* is a production-ready application, originally made for a real brick-and-mortar business. The UI has been designed with specific personas and jobs-to-be-done, and the usability has been user tested with employees.  
What you see is an anonymized and slightly generalized version, ready to be adopted to your specific needs, or used for reference. Full usability notes, user flows, and wireframes are included.

# CASE

*The Bakery* owns a centrally located café in addition to the actual bakery, which in turn is located outside the city center. 

In addition to daily producing a standard set of baked goods that can be bought fresh from the café or straight from the bakery, The Bakery is also the most well-known producer of cakes for special occasions, offering customization to a fairly wide variety of cakes in a few sizes.  
Most people just know (by rumor and experience) that you can order the cakes from the café, and go pick them up at the agreed upon date. 

Most don’t reflect on where (or when) the cakes are made, but the personnel is acutely aware; they need to get correct orders to the bakery, so that the customer gets what they ordered on the correct day \- and that day might be as simple as a workplace meeting, but quite often it’s a special occasion like a birthday or wedding. 

Orders need to be made just-in-time the morning when due, and messing up the order is no joke. 

Unfortunately the finer details and limitations of the bakery is sometimes learned the hard way, and the current process is based on handwritten notes passed along as photos in WhatsApp.

The Bakery needs an application to handle the order fulfillment for custom cakes, to ensure orders are correctly received, baked to spec and available the correct day.

# JOBS TO BE DONE

The customer does not interact directly with the system, leaving three main contexts:

1. Storefront  
   1. Accepting orders  
   2. Delivering (handing out) orders  
2. Bakery  
   1. Making orders due today  
   2. Reviewing/verifying incoming (new) orders  
   3. Secondary: accepting orders  
3. Backoffice (located at the bakery, but identified as a separate function)  
   1. Status / overview (decisionmaking, QA)  
   2. System administration  
   3. Secondary: accepting phone orders

The interactions with the system at the bakery basically consist of reviewing and changing the current state of order. We’ll work with the initial assumption that this context can be sufficiently addressed by the other two, not requiring it’s own screens. This assumption should be user tested.

**Jobs NOT to be done**

* No online store \- customer only plays an indirect role.  
* No shipping \- orders are always picked up by the customer.  
* No inventory, or functions to aid manufacturing.  
* No quick user switching, users are assumed to use personal devices or joint account (at the store)

**Jobs to be done**

* Storefront

      * For companies

# FLOWS

## Activities

**Login**  
All activities require the user to be logged in.

**Sell**  
Sell needs the most attention to streamline entry and avoid errors.

Login \-\> New order \-\> Add due date \-\> Choose items and details \-\> Enter (autofill) customer details \-\> Confirm 

* Entering a new order should be fast regardless of which state the application currently is in.   
* Due date is the first detail to be able to verify the feasibility of the order right away (Due tomorrow, and it’s evening now? No can do. Special order for the day after tomorrow? Might need to double-check with bakery.)  
* Autocompleting existing customers based on name / phone speeds up the process and avoids mistakes.  
* Autocomplete products. No separate product page at this point; customer will look at separate catalog of products, 

**Make and Deliver**  
Make and deliver are mostly about changing the state of the order. 

Login \-\> Find orders due \-\> Mark ‘in progress’ \-\> Mark ‘finished’ \-\> Mark ‘in store’

**View statistics and Admin**  
These are activities that manager-type persons are interested in, perhaps not even on a daily basis. (However, to allow mistakes and exceptional situations to be spotted by everyone, some form of readily available overview is useful for everyone.)

Login \-\> View statistics  
Login \-\> Administer users  
Login \-\> Administer products

## Order details

* Due date  
* Items  
  * Product  
  * Pcs  
  * Specs (decoration etc)  
* Price  
* Discount?  
* State  
  * New  
  * Verified  
  * Not OK 		(something wrong, needs attention)  
  * Cancelled 	(cancelled on purpose, no further action needed)  
  * In progress 	(a.k.a manufacturing)  
  * Ready 		(at bakery)  
  * In store 	(available for pickup)  
  * Delivered 	(picked up)  
* Paid (bool)

In rare cases, the order can be picked up, but not paid (e.g to be billed) or (even more seldom) wise versa. Hence Paid is a separate property.

# Scoping the App Template

It’s possible to adjust scope by simplifying some parts, and dropping some functionality \- especially functionality that is quite specific to this use case.

Simplifications that should not significantly affect the application as a complete example:

* No bulletin/status message (“post-it note”)  
* No VERIFIED- or PROBLEM-states  
  * Can be simplified all the way to NEW-\>AVAILABLE-\>DELIVERED \+ CANCELLED  
* No “pickup location” (assume one outlet)  
* No editing of placed Order, except via CRUD
